"and to prevent conflict between the groups" cannot be the sole motivation to direct corporatist policies; self-interest is one possible alternative motivation.
If "Corporatism" is a system of economic, political, or social organization, then it CANNOT establish policies SOLELY in the interest of the multiple groups and ALL of society.
"At a popular level in recent years" has neither supporting evidence, nor is the term objective.
"being alike to" is neither proper, nor needed.

Possible to have more than one competing corporation within a consortium--however, an organic body cannot have more than one competing liver.
"supported from various proponents" is biased and subjective. If "corporatism" is political, then it will comprise proponents and opponents, who support, or shun, the system.
"It" has no antecedent--however, "social, religious, economic, or popular organizations" was aforementioned.
"Directly or indirectly"? Any other options? No--The term goes.
Questionable antecedent to "their". Political scientists? States? Further attempts to split the run-on sentence.
"State" (Sovereign) and "Officially" is redundant. Poor use of hyphenation.

Clearly "the multiple groups" are neither the only interests that corporatism's economic, political, or social factors influence, nor is it under under any other economic, political, or social system.

Punctuation. Pronoun instead of antecedent reiteration. Delete redundant "Single Body".
"Private" business corporations is false--Corporations include those that have gone Public. Further, Government licenses these corporations--regardless of the interests of the public.
The adjective "pejorative" places a value on an otherwise objective description of a term. No "good"; no "bad"; no "pejorative";--only the facts.
Incongruous logic flow: If "Corpus" is the root, then "corporatism" and "corporation" share the root.
inaccurate and pejorative are not unbiased adjectives--they are, in fact,  inaccurate and pejorative.
